blockStates.name: The SEIR Model
blockStates.userText:
The SEIR model is a compartmental model 
in epidemiology that predicts the number 
of people infected with a contagious disease 
over time. It involves four compartments of
population: the susceptible population S, 
the exposed population E (not yet contagious), 
the infected population I (contagious), and 
the recovered population R. A SEIR model that 
considers birth and death rates can be written as:

dS/dt=λ-μS-βSI-ρS
dE/dt=βSI-(μ+α)E
dI/dt=αE-(μ+γ)I
dR/dt=γI-μR+ρS

where t is time, λ is the birth rate, μ is the death
rate, β is the exposure rate (contact rate), α is 
the infection rate, ρ is the vaccination rate, and 
γ is the recovery rate.

This page also shows how to define a time-varying
contact rate using a Function Declaration Block
that models the seasonal effect.

blockStates.name: Note
blockStates.userText:
The sum of the four populations
may grow or shrink depending on
the birth and death rates.
